  "prompt": "How you say lover in Hindi?",
  "response": "There isn't one single perfect word for \"lover\" in Hindi, as the best translation depends on the context and the specific nuance you want to convey. Here are a few options with explanations:\n\n*   **\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u092e\u0940 (premi):** This is probably the most common and generally understood translation for \"lover.\" It implies a romantic relationship and affection. It can be used for both male and female lovers.\n\n*   **\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u092e\u093f\u0915\u093e (premika):** This specifically means \"female lover\" or \"girlfriend.\" It's the feminine form of \"premi.\"\n\n*   **\u0906\u0936\u093f\u0915\u093c (aashiq):** This word implies a passionate, almost infatuated lover. It can sometimes carry a connotation of being a bit dramatic or even obsessive, but it also suggests deep affection. It's often used in poetry and literature.\n\n*   **\u092e\u0939\u092c\u0942\u092c (mehboob):** This word is more poetic and formal, often used in Urdu-influenced Hindi. It means \"beloved\" or \"darling.\" It can be used for either a male or female lover.\n\n*   **\u0926\u093f\u0932\u0930\u0941\u092c\u093e (dilruba):** Similar to \"mehboob,\" this is a more poetic and less common term that means \"one who steals the heart\" or \"beloved.\" It's more often used for a female lover.\n\nSo, to choose the best word, consider the context:\n\n*   For a general \"lover\" in a simple, straightforward sense, **\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u092e\u0940 (premi)** is often the best choice.\n*   If you need to specify a female lover, use **\u092a\u094d\u0930\u0947\u092e\u093f\u0915\u093e (premika).**\n*   For a more passionate, poetic, or Urdu-influenced expression, consider **\u0906\u0936\u093f\u0915\u093c (aashiq)** or **\u092e\u0939\u092c\u0942\u092c (mehboob).**",
